    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-01-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-01-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="588"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d588">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.21/1–1050: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-01-10">January 10,
                            1950</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>70. <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi> January 9, <hi rend="italic">Izvestiya</hi>
                    January 10 print New York Tass<note n="1" xml:id="d588fn1">Telegraph Agency of
                        the Soviet Union, the official communications organization of the Soviet
                        Government.</note> item headed “sharp deterioration economic position US” on
                    report economic advisers. Washington Tass item on President’s economic message
                        Congress,<note n="2" xml:id="d588fn2">The President’s annual economic report
                        was given to the Congress on January 6. For the text of the message, see <hi
                            rend="italic">Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States:
                            Harry S. Truman, 1950</hi> (Washington, Government Printing Office,
                        1965), pp. 18–31. The message and complete report were printed as <hi
                            rend="italic">The Economic Report of the President Transmitted to the
                            Congress, January 6, 1950</hi> (Washington, Government Printing Office,
                        1950).</note> total one column. Treatment same line as given State of Union
                        message<note n="3" xml:id="d588fn3">This address was delivered in person
                        before a joint session of the Congress on January 4. For the text, see <hi
                            rend="italic">Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States:
                            Harry S. Truman, 1950</hi>, pp. 2–11.</note> emphasizes drop production,
                    growth unemployment and strikes, deficit federal budget, housing shortage,
                    inadequacy Social Security, natural resources, education, health programs, drop
                    wages and farm income, increase military expenses, decline exports.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
